<topic id="d1e52"><title>Comment</title><body><p>
If you are not familiar with the concept of the derivative, read the first section of
<ph outputclass="a">Chapter 6</ph>
, and enter the function 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>exp</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 in the
<ph outputclass="a">applet</ph>
in section 6.1. Notice that 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>exp</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 has the property that it is its own derivative.
</p></body></topic>